'''Paul Hunter Barratt''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AO}} is a former senior Australian public servant and policymaker. He is currently Deputy Chairman of the [[Cooperative Research Centre for Advanced Composite Structures]] and Chairman of [[Australia 21]].

==Background and early life==
Paul Barratt, aged two, and his family moved to [[Armidale, New South Wales|Armidale]] in 1946.<ref>{{citation|title=Ida Madge Brown (1904-2009)|url=http://aussieobserver.blogspot.com.au/2009/12/ida-madge-brown-1904-2009.html|date=6 December 2009|work=Australian Observer|first=Paul|last=Barratt|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130506092131/http://aussieobserver.blogspot.com.au/2009/12/ida-madge-brown-1904-2009.html|archivedate=6 May 2013}}</ref>
He attended the Armidale Demonstration School between 1949 and 1955.<ref>{{citation|url=http://aussieobserver.blogspot.com.au/2011/06/armidale-demonstration-school-150th.html|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130429090117/http://aussieobserver.blogspot.com.au/2011/06/armidale-demonstration-school-150th.html|archivedate=29 April 2013|title=Armidale Demonstration School 150th anniversary|date=6 June 2011|work=Australian Observer|first=Paul|last=Barratt}}</ref> He sat his New South Wales Leaving Certificate at [[The Armidale School]] in 1960.<ref>{{citation|work=Australian Observer|url=http://aussieobserver.blogspot.com.au/2010/09/class-of-1960-fifty-years-on.html|title=The Class of 1960, fifty years on|date=19 September 2010|first=Paul|last=Barratt|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130425231608/http://aussieobserver.blogspot.com.au/2010/09/class-of-1960-fifty-years-on.html|archivedate=25 April 2013}}</ref>

In 1961 he begun his degree at the [[University of New England (Australia)|University of New England]], living in Wright College and graduating with an honours degree in physics.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.abc.net.au/unleashed/paul-barratt-2784854.html|title=Paul Barratt|archivedate=5 June 2013|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130605110922/http://www.abc.net.au/unleashed/paul-barratt-2784854.html|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Commission}}</ref><ref>{{citation|work=Australia Observer|first=Paul|last=Barratt|date=28 September 2013|archivedate=22 January 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20140122090832/http://aussieobserver.blogspot.com.au/2013/09/russell-ward-by-adhi-hendranto.html|url=http://aussieobserver.blogspot.com.au/2013/09/russell-ward-by-adhi-hendranto.html|title=Russell Ward by Adhi Hendranto}}</ref>

==Career==
Barratt joined his [[Australian Public Service|Commonwealth Public Sector]] the [[Department of Defence (Australia)|Department of Defence]] in 1966.<ref name=UNE>{{citation|url=http://www.une.edu.au/info-for/alumni/une-foundation/une-foundation-directors/mr-paul-barratt|title=Mr Paul Barratt|publisher=University of New England|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20140122084550/http://www.une.edu.au/info-for/alumni/une-foundation/une-foundation-directors/mr-paul-barratt|archivedate=22 January 2014}}</ref>

Between 1974 and 1985, Barratt was a Deputy Secretary in the [[Department of Trade (1983<U+2013>1987)|Department of Trade]] and accompanied Prime Minister [[Bob Hawke]] on his February 1984 visit to China.<ref>{{citation|url=http://aussieobserver.blogspot.com.au/2012/03/yellow-earth.html|title=Yellow Earth|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130430212947/http://aussieobserver.blogspot.com.au/2012/03/yellow-earth.html|archivedate=30 April 2013|date=29 March 2012|first=Paul|last=Barratt|work=Australian Observer}}</ref><ref name=UNE/>

Between 1992 and 1996 Barratt was Executive Director at the [[Business Council of Australia]].<ref name=UNE/> In 1996, Barratt rejoined the [[Australian Public Service]] as [[Departmental secretary|Secretary]] of the [[Department of Primary Industries and Energy]],<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://pmtranscripts.dpmc.gov.au/browse.php?did=9953|first=John|last=Howard|author-link=John Howard|date=8 March 1996|title=STATEMENT BY THE PRIME MINISTER DESIGNATE THE HON JOHN HOWARD MP |archivedate=10 November 2013|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20131110140511/http://pmtranscripts.dpmc.gov.au/browse.php?did=9953}}</ref> lured to the role by Prime Minister [[John Howard]], who was also a friend of Barratt's.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barratt's Attack On Government|newspaper=The Canberra Times|date=29 July 1999|publisher=Fairfax Media|page=8}}</ref> Barratt had accepted a $70,000 pay cut to return to the public sector.<ref name=SMH1999/>

Barratt transferred from the Department of Primary Industries and Energy to a second Secretary role in 1998, this time at the Department of Defence. 

Barratt was dismissed from his Secretary role at Defence in August 1999, with a letter saying he was being dismissed because his minister [[John Moore (Australian politician)|John Moore]] "had lost trust and confidence" in his abilities to perform his duties.<ref name=SMH1999>{{cite news|title=Campaign to sack Barratt relaunched|first1=Michelle|last1=Grattan|author-link1=Michelle Grattan|first2=Peter|last2=Cole-Adams|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=21 August 1999|page=8}}</ref> Barratt fought the dismissal, taking his case to the [[Federal Court of Australia|Federal Court]], but conceded defeat in March 2000 following rejection of his appeal.<ref>{{citation|page=9|title=DISMISSING A DEPARTMENTAL SECRETARY: AN OVERT EXERCISE OF POWER IN PUBLIC EMPLOYMENT|date=May 2004|first1=Len|last1=Pullin|first2=Ali|last2=Haidar|publisher=Monash University|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130512114110/http://www.buseco.monash.edu.au/mgt/research/working-papers/2004/wp32-04.pdf|archivedate=12 May 2013|url=http://www.buseco.monash.edu.au/mgt/research/working-papers/2004/wp32-04.pdf}}</ref>

Barratt is currently Deputy Chairman of the [[Cooperative Research Centre for Advanced Composite Structures]] and Chairman of [[Australia 21]].<ref name=NBLF>{{citation|url=http://www.nblf.com.au/2013-forum/speakers/|title=Speakers 2013|archivedate=8 August 2013|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130808050853/http://nblf.com.au/2013-forum/speakers/|publisher=National Business Leaders Forum on Sustainable Development}}</ref>

==Awards==
In 1999 Barratt was made an Officer of the Order of Australia for service to public administration, public policy development, business and international trade.<ref name=NBLF/>

